The Political Parties Disputes Tribunal has issued an order to reinstate Cleophas Malala as Senate Deputy Minority Leader until the case is heard and determined.  The court stayed the decision by ODM senators to remove him from office is null and void until the matter is heard and determined  The ANC senator was represented by LSK President Nelson Havi.  This means that the status quo remains, therefore, Speaker Lusaka will be required to effect the change as per the court orders which will see Kilifi Senator Stewart Madzayo vacate office.  Kakamega Sen. @Cleophasmalala met the Party Leader Hon @MusaliaMudavadi at Musalia Mudavadi Centre in Nairobi, today, moments after the Political Parties Disputes Tribunal issued orders reinstating him as the Senate Deputy Minority Leader until the case is heard & determined. pic.twitter.com/xTb1NU1NyG  Malala drums up support for One Kenya Alliance  My new position is good for Coast, says Madzayo  Now that he’s all cried out, Malala can play role of a stoic  Senator Isaac Mwaura loses bid to block ejection from Jubilee Party On March 24, ODM senators convened a Parliamentary Group meeting where they resolved to remove Malala as the deputy and vote in favour of Madzayo.  Malala was accused of alleged gross misconduct and mischief in the recently concluded Matungu parliamentary by-election.  Take a quick survey and help us improve our website!  James Orengo: Malala agreed he was only going to serve for one year in writing  "2022 nalenga kuwa President wa Jamhuri ya Kenya," ANC Party leader Musalia Mudavadi  POLICE STATE? Concern over arrest of 3 senators on day of revenue formula vote By Brian Otieno | 2 hours ago By Hassan Barisa | 3 hours ago By Patrick Vidija | 5 hours ago By Patrick Vidija and Jacob Ng'etich | 6 hours ago Read The Standard uninterrupted with no advertisements